ce:section.ce:para:
Coffee powder was purchased from commercial sources, used as a beverage, and the remaining grounds were recovered. After drying the recovered powder in an oven, the carbon content was determined using an elemental analyzer (Table 1
                        ). The coffee powder contained approximately 53 wt% carbon, which was sufficient as a raw material for the synthesis of CDs. The XRD pattern of the CDs synthesized from discarded coffee powder via hydrothermal synthesis is shown in Fig. 2
                        (a). The signal was observed in a wide range between 2θ = 15° and 30° and the main peak was 2θ = 21°, which was typical of the (002) plane of carbon. The lattice constant of the (002) plane of the XRD signal of bulk graphite is reported to be approximately 3.34 Å, whereas the CD of the nanoparticle d(002) size is approximately 4.22 Å. The synthesized CDs are reported to have a turbostratic structure and a structure similar to that of graphite, with interlayer spacing [26].
